content:
Certainly! Below is a simple HTML page that tests color vision. It displays a series of color swatches, allows users to select the closest matching color from a dropdown menu, and calculates a score at the end.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Color Vision Test</title>
    <style>
        .swatch {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            display: inline-block;
            margin: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #000;
        }
        #score {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-size: 20px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Color Vision Test</h1>
    <div id="swatches"></div>
    <button onclick="calculateScore()">Submit</button>
    <div id="score"></div>
    <div id="info"></div>

    <script>
        const colors = [
            { rgb: 'rgb(255, 0, 0)', name: 'Red' },
            { rgb: 'rgb(0, 255, 0)', name: 'Green' },
            { rgb: 'rgb(0, 0, 255)', name: 'Blue' },
            { rgb: 'rgb(255, 255, 0)', name: 'Yellow' },
            { rgb: 'rgb(0, 255, 255)', name: 'Cyan' },
            { rgb: 'rgb(255, 0, 255)', name: 'Magenta' },
        ];

        const swatchesContainer = document.getElementById('swatches');

        colors.forEach((color, index) => {
            const swatch = document.createElement('div');
            swatch.className = 'swatch';
            swatch.style.backgroundColor = color.rgb;

            const select = document.createElement('select');
            select.dataset.correct = color.name;
            ['Red', 'Green', 'Blue', 'Yellow', 'Cyan', 'Magenta'].forEach(optionName => {
                const option = document.createElement('option');
                option.value = optionName;
                option.textContent = optionName;
                select.appendChild(option);
            });

            swatchesContainer.appendChild(swatch);
            swatchesContainer.appendChild(select);
        });

        function calculateScore() {
            let score = 0;
            const selects = document.querySelectorAll('select');
            selects.forEach(select => {
                if (select.value === select.dataset.correct) {
                    score++;
                }
            });
            document.getElementById('score').textContent = `Your score: ${score} out of ${colors.length}`;

            if (score === colors.length) {
                document.getElementById('info').textContent = 'Congratulations! Humans can see up to 7 million different colors.';
            } else {
                document.getElementById('info').textContent = 'Try again! Humans can see up to 7 million different colors.';
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **Color Swatches**: The page generates a series of color swatches using an array of objects, each containing an RGB value and a color name.
- **Dropdown Menu**: For each swatch, there is a dropdown menu where users can select the color name they believe matches the swatch.
- **Score Calculation**: When the user clicks the "Submit" button, the script calculates how many selections were correct and displays the user's score.
- **Color Vision Fact**: Depending on the score, it shows a message about human color vision capabilities.

Feel free to expand or customize the list of colors and adjust the styles as needed!
